An Introductory example: ggplot2

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = disp, y = mpg)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue") +
  geom_smooth(color = "darkblue", size = 1)
geom_smooth: method="auto" and size of largest group is <1000, so using loess. Use 'method = x' to change the smoothing method.

Same example in ggvis

mtcars %>% ggvis(x = ~ disp, y = ~ mpg) %>%
  layer_points(stroke := "blue", size := 50) %>%
  layer_smooths(stroke := "darkblue", 
                strokeWidth := 3, se = TRUE)

What is ggvis?

  • an R package for web-based graphics
  • based on the Vega visualization system in JavaScript
  • brought to you by the lead developers of ggplot2.

ggvis is a fusion of:

  • the grammar of graphics from ggplot2
  • reactive programming from shiny
  • data transformation pipelines from dplyr

What is ggvis? (cont.)

Each ggvis function takes a visualization object as input and returns a modified visualization as output.

p <- InsectSprays %>% ggvis(x = ~ spray, y = ~ count)
p <- layer_boxplots(p, fill = ~ spray)
p

Contrasts between ggvis and ggplot2

ggvis ggplot2
web graphics presentation graphics
static or reactive graphics static graphics
evolving mature
rendering: Vega visualization (JS) rendering: R grid graphics

Basic constructs in ggvis

  • fundamental building block in ggvis is the mark

  • draws a specific type of geometric object

  • a layer draws graphical content in a ggvis
  • simple layers (wrappers for marks)

  • compound layers (marks + statistical/data transformation)

  • compute_*() functions perform statistical transformations
  • scale_*() functions modify how data values are mapped to the visual space (relative to defaults)

  • input_*() functions generate interactive objects such as checkboxes, sliders or input boxes.

Syntax

  • symbol ~ means that the variable to be assigned should be taken from the current data object;
  • symbol = means that the value assigned to a mark is to be mapped to a scaled value (i.e., in data units);
  • the symbol := means that the value assigned to a mark is set to an unscaled value independent of data units.

More accurately, ~ means "capture the expression for later evaluation in the context of the data".

Warning: Using := when = is appropriate, or vice versa, can produce very different behavior.

Grouping

  • in ggplot2, grouping was handled with a group aesthetic
  • in ggvis, grouping is a data transformation
  • use group_by() in the data pipeline

Marks and properties

  • seven basic marks in ggvis
  • marks are endowed with properties
  • each property has one or more values.
  • this hierarchy increases the flexibility of ggvis

Basic marks and simple layers

Mark Layer related ggplot2 geoms
mark_area() layer_areas() geom_ribbon(), geom_area()
mark_path() layer_paths() geom_path(), geom_line()
mark_rect() layer_rects() geom_rect(), geom_bar(), geom_tile()
mark_point() layer_points() geom_point()
mark_text() layer_text() geom_text()
mark_arc() layer_arcs() (draws arcs/curves)
mark_image() layer_images() (imports image from file/URL)

compute_*() functions

  • perform statistical transformations on the input data
  • compute_*() functions are data transformations
  • results can be passed along the data pipeline
  • illustrates the enriched types of (hierarchical) data structures supported by ggvis

compute_*() functions (cont.)

  • compute_align: align positions using length
  • compute_bin: bin data along a continuous variable
  • compute_boxplot: compute values needed for a boxplot
  • compute_count: count data at fixed numeric locations
  • compute_density: compute kernel density estimate
  • compute_model_prediction: compute predicted values from a statistical model of one variable
  • compute_smooth: compute predicted values for a loess model
  • compute_stack: compute inputs for stacked bar/area charts
  • compute_tabulate: count data at each level of a factor or categorical variable

Compound layers

Function Composition
layer_bars() layer_rects() + compute_tabulate()
layer_boxplots() compute_boxplot() + several simple layers
layer_densities() compute_density() + layer_paths()
layer_freqpolys() compute_bin() + layer_paths()
layer_histograms() compute_bin() + layer_rects()
layer_lines() dplyr::arrange() + layer_paths()
layer_model_predictions() compute_model_prediction() + layer_lines()
layer_smooths() compute_smooth() + layer_areas() + layer_lines()

  ggvis(x = ~ displ, y = ~ hwy, fill = ~ Cyl) %>%

Side note re positioning of mark properties

Mark properties set/mapped inside ggvis() are intended to be global—i.e., they are meant to persist across layers.

Mark properties that are meant to be local to an individual layer are defined as part of the specification of that layer.

mpg %>%
  ggvis(x = ~ cyl, y = ~ hwy) %>%  # global assignments
  layer_boxplots(width = 0.5, fill = ~ factor(cyl)) # local assignments

Data pipeline + visualization

Smoothers

filter(mpg1, Cyl != 5) %>%
    ggvis(x = ~ displ, y = ~ hwy) %>%
    layer_smooths(strokeWidth := 3, se = TRUE) %>%  # overall 
    group_by(Cyl) %>%    
    layer_points(fill = ~ Cyl, stroke = ~ Cyl,
                   fillOpacity := 0.4, strokeOpacity := 0.7) %>%
    layer_smooths(stroke = ~ Cyl)

Interactivity

Interactivity functions in ggvis

  • input_checkbox(): creates a single-item checkbox
  • input_checkboxgroup(): creates a multi-item checkbox group
  • input_numeric(): creates an interactive box for numeric input
  • input_radiobuttons(): creates a box composed of radio buttons
  • input_select(): creates a multiple selection box
  • input_slider(): creates an interactive slider
  • input_text(): creates an interactive text box

Example 1: Histogram with slider

Copy/paste code from script file to run interactively:

slider_box <- input_slider(0.5, 10, value = 3, 
                           step = 0.5, label = "Bin width")
mpg %>% ggvis(x = ~ hwy) %>%
        layer_histograms(width = slider_box, fill := "darkorange")

Example 2: Loess smooth with slider

# input_ function defined as a property 'value'
mpg %>% ggvis(x = ~ displ, y = ~ hwy) %>%
        layer_points(fillOpacity := 0.3) %>%
        layer_smooths(stroke := "blue", strokeWidth := 2,
                      span = input_slider(0.2, 1, 
                               value = 0.5, label = "Span" ))

Tooltips

  • display information about the data associated with a geometric object

The game is to:

  • write a function that determines how the tooltip behaves;
  • call it in a layer function with additional arguments concerning tooltips.

Example: Display data values

# Function to specify what is to be visualized when a
# point is hovered over
all_values <- function(x)
{
    if(is.null(x)) return(NULL)
    paste0(names(x), ": ", format(x), collapse = "<br />")
}

mtcars %>% ggvis(x = ~ wt, y = ~ mpg) %>%
           layer_points(fill.hover := "red") %>%
           add_tooltip(all_values, "hover")

Shiny integration

ggvis and shiny

  • can use shiny reactives to create a ggvis object

  • can embed ggvis graphics in a Shiny app

  • In functional reactive programming, a reactive can input values from another reactive, thus producing a dependency chain
  • the reactives persist

  • when the value of an ancestor node changes, all descendants are recomputed

ggvis where data is reactive

dat <- data.frame(time = 1:10, value = runif(10))

# Create a reactive that returns a data frame, adding a new
# row every 0.5 seconds
ddat <- reactive({
  invalidateLater(500, NULL)
  dat$time <<- c(dat$time[-1], dat$time[length(dat$time)] + 1)
  dat$value <<- c(dat$value[-1], runif(1))
  dat
})
ddat %>% ggvis(x = ~time, y = ~value, key := ~time) %>%
  layer_points() %>%
  layer_paths()
